summary: ok so we know that Crowley loved Aziraphale day one (1) six thousand years ago.  Crowley’s been pining and mad at the whole...
body:
ok so we know that Crowley loved Aziraphale day one (1) six thousand years ago.  Crowley’s been pining and mad at the whole situation the entire time.

Aziraphale, however, was peak dumbass the entire time.  

Aziraphale throughout the slow centuries, “Gosh, I know Crowley’s a demon, but he’s such a nice fellow deep down.  He’s ever so clever and funny.  It’s a bit funny how he always makes me smile.  Also it’s so weird how the feeling of love intensifies whenever he’s around.  Funny coincidence, that.  Those humans, eh? Always up to something.  Crowley’s actually a pretty decent chap.”  :-)

[Crowley’s muffled screaming plays in the distance]

Aziraphale starts to notice his feelings a bit in the 1800′s when Crowley asks for holy water, he’s crushed and furious at him for all the implications.

But finally Aziraphale has the Epiphany™ in the church ruins when Crowley casually, with a hidden smile, hands a distraught Aziraphale his precious books, which Crowley had saved from the nazis.  

A look of soft wonder came over his face as he finally realized he loved Crowley.

Fast forward to the 60s, when Crowley offered to take him anywhere he wanted, anywhere at all.

And all Aziraphale can think of is that he’s only know for sure that he’s been in love with Crowley for 20 years, a month in the time frame of immortals. 

Crowley’s been there waiting for Aziraphale to realize his feelings, patiently, for all the long millennia, and when Aziraphale told him he goes too fast, he just quietly sits there and will continue to wait until the end of the world if need be.

GOD

summary: Just imagine Crowley and Aziraphale co-parenting a child
title: Just imagine Crowley and Aziraphale co-parenting a child
body:
• They find the abandoned baby in a box outside Aziraphale’s shop, nobody knows how they got there.
  • Aziraphale immediately panics, he doesn’t have much experience with children, and less with babies. Crowley is in a chill panic.
  • After they can’t found anyone that is related to the baby or is at least able to take care of them, they decide to keep it. (Actually, it was Crowley’s idea. “If we are going to pose as humans we may as well pretend to have progeny”)
  • Both are disaster bumbling dads. Couldn’t change a nappy even if their lifes depended on it. Lucky for them they are supernatural beings with mystical powers.
  • Aziraphale likes to read to the baby, a lot. He wants them to love literature as much as he loves it. He even makes the voices for the characters even if he is reading them Franklin’s almanac.
  • Crowley is in charge of braiding the kid’s hair and dressing them up. If he is going to be a dad, then his child will be the most fashionable kid in the entire world. He always make sure to dress the kid in lighter colours, since it reminds him of his angel.
  • The kid’s sountrack of their life is basically Queen’s. (And Crowley’s lullabies)
  • Aziraphale would be the kind of dad to worry about everything. And when I say everything I mean EVERYTHING. Is he good enough? is the kid happy? Do they love Crowley more than him? Do they love him more than Crowley? are they safe? aren’t they hurt? why aren’t they answering him? Oh God, something has happe-
  • First day of school and Aziraphale absolutely P A N I C S. Crowley pretends to be chill, but if anyone dares to insinuate to his angel that he pretended to be the science class’ pet snake for the whole day just to watch over his baby, he will hunt them down and put the fear of Crowley into them.
  • Bullies? Aziraphale deals with them, before Crowley is able to get to them. Just a soft smile and a little chat in private, and they will never approach their child again.
  • They don’t push their kid towards any religion. They just want them to grow up safe and happy, and to choose what to believe in. Their kid turns out to be Buddhist and while Aziraphale smiles awkwardly in acceptance, Crowley is basically roaring with laughter, and loves their kid 3 million times afterwards.
  • Their kid grows up and start high school and with high school comes a parent’s worst nightmare: the boyfriends/ girlfriend.
  • They are not against any kind of sexual orientation the kid may have. They just hate that someone is going to snatch their baby away from them.
  • Aziraphale is more moderate, and will treat their kid’s partners with extreme politeness and respect, but he will not tolerate any kind of wrongdoing towards their child.
  • Crowley is more open about his extreme hate towards his kid’s romantic partner. He would glare daggers at any potential boyfriend or girlfriend, and try to intimidate them with his demonic powers, but will stop if his angel asks him to or if he is upsetting their kid.
  • Their child knows what they are and that they will probably outlive their own progeny. Despite that thought clearly makes Azi and Crowley feel distressed, their child is just happy they got to live with the best dads in the entire world, and knows that should anything happen, they can always count on them.

summary: Aziraphale and Crowley being angelic and demonic everymen, respectively, is very good, if not quite low on any sort of totem...
body:
Aziraphale and Crowley being angelic and demonic everymen, respectively, is very good, if not quite low on any sort of totem pole, but possibly better is Aziraphale and Crowley both being significantly more powerful than either of them realize - probably more than their bosses realize.

There are infinite possible mechanical explanations, if you want. Angelic/demonic power is kind of like a muscle, and they exercise it far more on Earth than anyone does in Heaven or Hell, either because they just do more or because it takes more effort to do the same thing (moving through water vs air.) Proper angelic power is based on love and fallen angelic power on hate, which as we know is almost the same thing, and over 6000 years with humans, Aziraphale and Crowley have developed a whole lot more of both than anyone else. Maybe it’s that they intuitively understand more of the Ineffable Plan than anyone else, even if they don’t realize it, and that counts for something. Or maybe there’s just been a lot of Discworld-style belief invested, over the millennia, in the only two supernatural beings any human actually met. (Particularly, tbh, mythologically, in the Snake. Aziraphale needs to keep up.)

They could probably singly and certainly together kick the ass of pretty much anyone in Heaven or Hell. Not all of them at once, though. Unfortunately.
